    <prp:abstract>The earliest, most massive galaxies to form in the universe present a sharp puzzle, as there is apparently insufficient time to form their stellar masses by the time at which they are observed.  We propose observations of C{\small II} emission to trace star formation in and around S551281, the single most robust detection of a high-redshift, high-mass galaxy to date.  Mapping the star formation will provide a major improvement in our ability to model the formation of these seemingly impossible galaxies, as well as the ``clumpyness factor'' critical for models of reionization.</prp:abstract>
